5. The download completes, and the `.json` file is now populated with data.
6. On the next refresh, `getLocalTrips` runs again. This time, `currentFile.length() > 0` is true, the trip is included in the list, and it reappears on the screen.

To solve this, we need to make the file download an atomic operation. The standard way to do this is to download the file to a temporary name (e.g., `ORD000004.json.tmp`) and then, only when the download is 100% complete, rename it to its final name (`ORD000004.json`). A file rename is an atomic operation on most filesystems, meaning it happens instantly.

This ensures that the `getLocalTrips` method will never encounter a partially downloaded file. It will either not see the file at all (when it has a `.tmp` extension) or it will see the complete, valid file.

